Let me tell you about our incredibly talented artist, and my dear friend @theartofnicolasmartin from France. I had the idea of inviting Nicolas to our 2017 Americans in Paris events in Paris. He was the only Frenchman to join our group of 12 American artists. His perspective and dedication to fine art is commendable. He spends countless hours in his studio and is truly dedicated to creating top quality work for various shows and exhibitions throughout the world. I was able to write an article celebrating his work and dedication And will continue to write and celebrate his work, shown here. He is very talented at creating portraits in capturing a special moment in life, such as when I was writing my lecture notes at the Grand Chaumiere in Paris, and when my father passed away I commissioned him to create one of my father with his steel guitar. We are honored to have him as an integral part of the Americans in Paris group exhibitions and events and look forward to his new works being created now for our fashion exhibition in New York opening April 16 at the Salmagundi Club. More works are currently available at our gallery in the interiors section @vanessarothe #vanessarothefineart

We have a very exciting announcement and are finally able to share that Vanessa Rothe Fine Art had been contacted to be a part of a movie being created. “Movement, light, and Life” Written and Directed by @winston_stemler.  Info below. 
As an associate producer of the film and fine artist, I’m proud to have helped them create an authentic 19th century studio, plein air scenes, painted and supplied actual fine art in the film by the artists listed below, and my studio props. This amazing film is currently in production: A period romance “Movement, Light, and Life” follows the story of a young Impressionist painter in the 19th century. The year is 1889. In the countryside of France, a young Impressionist painter, Paul Lefay, is tasked by the famed Academie des Beaux-Arts to complete his first ever commission. Troubled by a lack of inspiration and searching for a muse to inspire his greatest painting yet, Paul journeys down to the local riverbank where he meets a fellow painter, the radiant and consummately talented Annabelle Veilleux. There, on a beautiful summer morn, the two lock eyes and the root of their love takes hold... Drawing from the works of real-life Impressionists, Movement, Light, and Life is a period romance short film set in the 19th Century. A tale of love, passion, and inspiration about two painters, the film aims to capture the essence of a bygone era and celebrate the transformative power of art.  The fine artists involved in the film that we have chosen and work appears in the film are : Derek Harrison, Vanessa Rothe, Ray Roberts, Cheryl Klein, Sharen Weaver and Brian Spadafora. The trailer is currently being produced and we will keep you posted on information regarding this film with high quality most authentic fine art and studio seen in a movie. More posts of the work by various artists are soon to follow and keep an eye out for this amazing film by Stemler and his genius team. @movement_light_and_life @vanessarothe @derekharrisonart @ray_roberts @kleincheryl @sharonweaverart @4_of_spades. Contemporary realists works are evolving again. Back in 2016 realists were really being brave and dabbling with abstraction making all abstract works. But in today’s works they are taking it a step further …by keeping/guarding their incredible realism skills and then adding bold abstraction to it with two sides of the coin together as one crossing over different genres and boundaries. They are not abstracting everything but keeping their incredible realism and adding instruction either around it on top of it or within it. These two polar opposites are combined together to make an incredible new work of art.  Enjoy my new article out in American art collector magazine January edition where I discuss what is going on today with contemporaryrealism in 2023 with artwork by Vincent xeus, J Louis, Quang Ho, Timothy Reese and my talented French friend Bertrand Martin
